To find out optimal locations for opening a chinese restaurant in Toronto¶

Table of contents¶

  • 1. Introduction: Business Problem
  • 2. Data
  • 3. Method
  • 4. Analysis
  • 5. Results and Discussion
  • 6. Conclusion

1. Introduction: Business Problem ¶

We will try to find out an optimal location for opening a restaurant in this project. We hope that this project is valuable to potential investors who are interested in opening a Chinese restaurant in Toronto, Canada.

We think that a good location for opening a new Chinese restaurant should meet the following conditions:

First, it is not already crowded with restaurants there;

Second, there is no more than 1 Chinese restaurant already there;

Last, it is as close as possible to the city centre;

We will use our data science skills and tools to find out a few most promissing neighborhoods based on this criterias.In order to facilitate the potential investors to choose the best location for opening the Chinese restaurant, we will clearly show the advantages of each area.

2. Data ¶

Based on definition of our problem, factors that will influence our decission are:

number of existing restaurants in the neighborhood (any type of restaurant)

number of and distance to Chinese restaurants in the neighborhood, if any

distance of neighborhood from city center

We decided to use regularly spaced grid of locations, centered around city center, to define our neighborhoods.

Following data sources will be needed to extract/generate the required information:

centers of candidate areas will be generated algorithmically and approximate addresses of centers of those areas will be obtained using GeoPy.

number of restaurants and their type and location in every neighborhood will be obtained using Foursquare API

coordinate of Toronto center will be obtained using GeoPy geocoding of 'Toronto,Canada'.

Neighborhood Candidates¶

Let's create latitude & longitude coordinates for centroids of our candidate neighborhoods. We will create a grid of cells covering our area of interest which is aprox. 20 x 20 kilometers centered around Toronto center.

Now let's create a grid of area candidates, equaly spaced, centered around city center and within ~8km from Toronto centre. Our neighborhoods will be defined as circular areas with a radius of 500 meters, so our neighborhood centers will be 1000 meters apart.

We will use GeoPy to calculate distance.

In [4]:
distance_to_centre=10000 # The area which is aprox. 20 x 20 kilometers centered around Toronto center.
radius_cell = 1000
k = distance_to_centre/radius_cell
lat_step = 0.00900544 # Every 1000 meters in the north-south direction, the latitude changes by about 0.00900544.
lon_step = 0.01171056 # Every 1000 meters in the east-west direction, the longitude changes by about 0.01171056.
lat_min = Toronto_centre_lat - k*lat_step
lat_max = Toronto_centre_lat + k*lat_step
lon_min = Toronto_centre_lon - k*lon_step
lon_max = Toronto_centre_lon + k*lon_step

latitudes = []
longitudes = []
distances_from_center = []

for i in range(0,int(2*k+1)):
    lat = lat_min + i * lat_step
    for j in range(0,int(2*k+1)):
        lon = lon_min + j * lon_step
        distance_from_center = (distance.distance((Toronto_centre_lat,Toronto_centre_lon), (lat,lon)).km)*1000
        latitudes.append(lat)
        longitudes.append(lon)
        distances_from_center.append(distance_from_center)

print(len(latitudes), 'candidate neighborhood centers generated.')

def is_restaurant(categories, specific_filter=None):
    restaurant_words = ['restaurant', 'diner', 'taverna', 'steakhouse']
    restaurant = False
    specific = False
    for c in categories:
        category_name = c[0].lower()
        category_id = c[1]
        for r in restaurant_words:
            if r in category_name:
                restaurant = True
        if 'fast food' in category_name:
            restaurant = False
        if not(specific_filter is None) and (category_id in specific_filter):
            specific = True
            restaurant = True
    return restaurant, specific

def get_categories(categories):
    return [(cat['name'], cat['id']) for cat in categories]

def format_address(location):
    address = ', '.join(location['formattedAddress'])
    address = address.replace(', Canada', '')
    return address

def get_venues_near_location(lat, lon, category, radius=500, limit=100):
    url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/explore?client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&category={}&radius={}&limit={}'.format(
        CLIENT_ID, CLIENT_SECRET, VERSION, lat, lon, category, radius, limit)
    try:
        results = requests.get(url).json()['response']['groups'][0]['items']
        venues = [(item['venue']['id'],
                   item['venue']['name'],
                   get_categories(item['venue']['categories']),
                   (item['venue']['location']['lat'], item['venue']['location']['lng']),
                   format_address(item['venue']['location']),
                   item['venue']['location']['distance']) for item in results]        
    except:
        venues = []
    return venues

# Let's now go over our neighborhood locations and get nearby restaurants; we'll also maintain a dictionary of all found restaurants and all found Chinese restaurants

def get_restaurants(lats, lons):
    restaurants = {}
    chinese_restaurants = {}
    location_restaurants = []

    print('Obtaining venues around candidate locations:', end='')
    for lat, lon in zip(lats, lons):
        # Using radius=500 to meke sure we have overlaps/full coverage so we don't miss any restaurant (we're using dictionaries to remove any duplicates resulting from area overlaps)
        venues = get_venues_near_location(lat, lon, food_category, radius=500, limit=100)
        area_restaurants = []
        for venue in venues:
            venue_id = venue[0]
            venue_name = venue[1]
            venue_categories = venue[2]
            venue_latlon = venue[3]
            venue_address = venue[4]
            venue_distance = venue[5]
            is_res, is_chinese = is_restaurant(venue_categories, specific_filter=chinese_restaurant_categories)
            if is_res:
                restaurant = (venue_id, venue_name, venue_latlon[0], venue_latlon[1], venue_address, venue_distance, is_chinese)
                if (abs(venue_latlon[0]-lat)<=lat_step/1000*500) and (abs(venue_latlon[1]-lon)<=lon_step/1000*500):
                    area_restaurants.append(restaurant)
                restaurants[venue_id] = restaurant
                if is_chinese:
                    chinese_restaurants[venue_id] = restaurant
        location_restaurants.append(area_restaurants)
        print(' .', end='')
    print(' done.')
    return restaurants, chinese_restaurants, location_restaurants

3. Method ¶

In this project we will direct our efforts on detecting areas of Toronto that have low restaurant density, particularly those with low number of Chinese restaurants. We will limit our analysis to area 20 x 20 kilometers around the city centre.

In first step we have collected the required data: location and type (category) of every restaurant within 10km fom Toronto centre. We have also identified Chinsese restaurants according to Foursquare categorization.

Second step in our analysis will be calculation and exploration of 'restaurant density' across different neighbours of Toronto.we will use heatmaps to identify a few promising neighbours close to city centre with low number of restaurants in general (and no Chinese restaurants in vicinity) and focus our attention on those neighbourhoods.

In third and final step we will focus on most promising neighbourhoods and within those create clusters of locations that meet some basic requirements established in discussion with potential investors: we will take into consideration locations with more than zero but no more than two restaurants in radius of 500 meters(This means this is a neighbourhood where catering services can be provided), and we want locations without Chinese restaurants in radius of 1000 meters but with only one Chinese restaurants in 2000 meters(This means there are a certain amount customers who like Chinese food in this neighbourhood, and the competition with Chinese restaurant is not very fierce in this neighbourhood.) . We will present map of all such locations but also create clusters (using k-means clustering) of those locations to identify general zones / neighborhoods / addresses which should be a starting point for final 'street level' exploration and search for optimal venue location by potential investors.

5. Results and Discussion ¶

Our analysis shows that there is 940 restaurants included 37 chinese restaurants in our initial area which was 20x20km around Toronto centre.

In order to find out the optimal location for openning the chinese restaurant, we first divide the 20x20km area around Toronto centre into 441 squrares by 1x1 km as city neighbourhoods. Since 147 squares of these are on the sea with zero population, so we have 294 city neighbourhoods. Then we find out 70 city neighbourhoods where catering services can be provided and restaurant density is low. Next,we find 17 city neigbourhoods suitable for openning a chinese restaurant,where there are a certain amount customers who like Chinese food near this neighbourhood( there are some chinese restaurants in 2 kilometers of this neighbourhood center), and the competition with Chinese restaurant is not very fierce near this neighbourhood(there are zero chinese restaurant in 1 kilometers and only 1 chinese restaurant in 2 kilometers of this neighbourhood center).Lastly,we use cluster method to find out 6 optimal neighbourhoods for openning a new chinese restaurant near the Toronto centre.

But,this, of course, does not mean that those neighbourhoods are actually optimal locations for a new restaurant,because we ignored some important factors such as traffic ,population density and population structure, etcs.

6. Conclusion ¶

Purpose of this project was to identify Toronto areas close to center with low restaurant density (estpecialy chinese restaurant denstiy) and with Chinese food taste in order to help the potential investors to search for optimal location for a new Chinese restaurant.

Final decission on optimal restaurant location will be made by the potential investors based on specific characteristics of neighborhoods and locations in every recommended zone, taking into consideration additional factors like attractiveness of each location (proximity to park or water), traffic, population density, population structure,levels of noise / proximity to major roads etc.
